# Miro Board, a tool to help teams brainstorm, plan, and work together remotely

## Reference: Where can we find more information or download materials?

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)



Miro is a web-based collaborative whiteboard platform designed to help teams brainstorm, plan, and work together remotely. Think of it as a giant digital whiteboard that multiple people can access and edit simultaneously. Here are some key features of Miro boards:  
  
Visual Collaboration: People can add sticky notes, mind maps, drawings, images, and documents to the board.  
  
Real-time Editing: Everyone can see changes made to the board as they happen, fostering a sense of shared space.  
  
Templates: Miro offers a library of pre-built templates to get you started on common tasks like brainstorming sessions, user journey maps, and flowcharts.  
  
Integrations: It integrates with other popular tools like Slack, Jira, and Google Drive, allowing you to easily import and export information.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)



Miro boards are valuable in R&amp;D for a few reasons: Visual Collaboration, Remote Brainstorming, Centralized Idea Capture, Building on Ideas, and Project Organization.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)



Miro board is a tool for remote teams to brainstorm, plan, and collaborate. It provides a visual workspace where everyone can contribute and see ideas develop in real-time.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?



Here's a breakdown on how R&amp;D teams can leverage Miro boards to boost their innovation process:  
  
1. Define the Goal &amp; Invite Collaborators  
  
2. Choose a Template or Build Your Board:  
  
3. Brainstorming &amp; Capturing Ideas  
  
4. Organize &amp; Refine  
  
5. Action &amp; Iteration  
  
6. Document your learnings

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)



Here are some key things to keep in mind when using Miro boards for R&amp;D purposes:  
  
Focus &amp; Facilitation: While Miro fosters free-flowing ideas, a clear focus on the R&amp;D objective keeps brainstorming productive. A facilitator can guide discussions and ensure everyone stays on track  
  
Balance Creativity &amp; Feasibility: Miro excels at sparking wild ideas, but don't neglect feasibility. Later stages can involve evaluating practicality and potential impact to refine the most promising concepts.  
  
Documentation &amp; Version Control: Capture key decisions and discussions within the Miro board using notes or text boxes. Utilize version control features to track changes and avoid confusion.  
  
Security &amp; Access Control: If dealing with sensitive information, ensure proper security settings are in place on your Miro board. Limit access only to authorized R&amp;D team members.  
  
Integration with Other Tools: Take advantage of Miro's integrations with project management or document sharing tools to streamline your R&amp;D workflow and centralize relevant information.

## Reflections: What to keep in mind when using the tool for R&amp;D purposes?



Focus &amp; Facilitate: Maintain a clear R&amp;D goal and guide brainstorming to prevent tangents.  
  
Balance Creativity &amp; Reality: Encourage wild ideas, but prioritize based on feasibility and impact later.

Security &amp; Access: Limit access to authorized personnel for sensitive information.  
  
Integrations: Leverage Miro's connections to streamline workflow and centralize data.

## Credit: Who developed the tool or method?



The concept behind Miro boards wasn't developed by a single person, but rather emerged from the work of Andrey Khusid.  
  
In 2011, Khusid, who co-founded the company behind Miro (originally called RealtimeBoard), needed a way for his design agency to collaborate on ideas with clients remotely. This need led to the development of the initial virtual whiteboard that eventually evolved into the robust Miro platform we know today.

# Miro

## Image: What does it look like?

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Reference: Where can we find more information or download materials?

<a href="https://miro.com/" target=" blank">https://miro.com/</a>

## Description: What is it? (max 1,500 characters)

Miro is an online whiteboard platform that enables multi-user, synchronous and asynchronous collaboration. It is very user friendly, and generally does not lag when many users are connected. Miro is also useful for individual use, for example for creating mind maps.

## Purpose: Why do we use this method or tool for R&amp;D? (max 1,500 characters)

We use Miro for virtual workshop and trainings. It is a replacement for in-person sticky-note-based activities. We sometimes also use Miro for mind-mapping.

## Summary: Describe in one sentence, what it is and what it does? (max 120 characters)

Miro is an online whiteboard that facilitates collaboration.

## Instructions: How is it used for R&amp;D? What steps to follow?

Miro  has many templates (or canvases) that allow you to quickly set up an online workshop. It also possible to make your own canvases. However, make sure to lock all structural canvas elements before running a session. Also, make sure you precede your workshops or brainstorming sessions with instructions and make sure there are enough instructions on the whiteboard for independent individual work.

## Requirements: What is needed to effectively use it for R&amp;D? (e.g. skills, conditions, inputs, resources)

A relatively powerful desktop or laptop computer and a stable internet connection. It also good to have some experience in designing and conducting workshops.
